Former Roads minister Franklin Bett has said the selling of the Jubilee Party smartcards by aspirants would interfere with the party nominations.The one-time State House Comptroller on Saturday said the current mode of buying the cards will only favour the rich candidates.He said all those seeking JP nominations should be accorded an equal opportunity to get the cards. Each smart membership card costs Sh20.Bett also announced his candidature for Kericho Senator when he met 200 supporters from Bureti constituency. &ldquo;I have vast experience, both in the political arena and in the civil service. My election will give this county a better chance to spur development,&rdquo; he said. During the Senate by-election two years ago, Bett and Sammy Chepkwony lost the URP ticket nomination to Aaron Cheruiyot.